=== #12 packages/credentials-admin-routes/src/destination-routes.ts:126 ===
_⚠️ Potential issue_ | _🟠 Major_ | _⚡ Quick win_

<details>
<summary>🧩 Analysis chain</summary>

🌐 Web query:

`In Node.js, does `Buffer.from(value, 'base64')` reject malformed base64 input, or can it silently ignore invalid characters / return truncated output? Please answer from official Node.js documentation.`

💡 Result:

Yes—per official Node.js Buffer documentation, `Buffer.from(value, 'base64')` does not reject malformed base64; it “assumes valid input” and decoding is lenient (it can ignore whitespace and may produce a result even when non-base64 characters are present). [1] Specifically, Node’s docs state: 1) For `'base64'`/`'base64url'`/`'hex'`, “this function assumes valid input.” [1] 2) When creating a Buffer from a string using `'base64'`, “Whitespace characters such as spaces, tabs, and new lines … are ignored.” [1] 3) For strings containing non-base64/hex-encoded data (example given: “whitespace”), “the return value might be greater than the length of a Buffer created from the string.” [1] So Node’s official documentation indicates it will not necessarily throw on malformed base64, and invalid/non-base64 characters (at least whitespace) can be ignored rather than causing rejection or error.

Citations:

- 1: https://nodejs.org/api/buffer.html

