**Reject malformed base64 instead of letting `Buffer.from` silently coerce it.**

`Buffer.from(value, 'base64')` is lenient per Node.js documentation: it assumes valid input and can ignore invalid characters, so malformed base64 will decode to truncated or unexpected bytes. This route will return `204` while storing a different secret than the caller sent. The try-catch at lines 205-210 only guards against thrown exceptions, not silent coercion.

Add strict base64 validation (e.g., regex format check + round-trip verification) before decoding, and add a regression test for malformed-but-decodable inpu

